{
  "case_id": "D2N104",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nOngoing management of psoriatic arthritis and concerns regarding recent bruising.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports ongoing management of psoriatic arthritis and reports decreasing her prednisone dose. She experienced occasional extra prednisone doses due to foot pain when engaging in desk work. She also reports receiving a COVID vaccine, which resulted in significant pain and required a second dose a week later. The patient recently noticed new bruises appearing without apparent trauma and inquired about their cause. She reports that prednisone may be contributing to increased bruising. She reports that methotrexate has helped with joint pain. The patient's nails also show ridges consistent with psoriasis.\n\nFindings\nExamination reveals good range of motion in the toes and nails. No acute physical exam findings were noted.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient is diagnosed with psoriatic arthritis and is experiencing related symptoms including bruising and nail changes.\n\nPlan\nWe will continue the current methotrexate regimen and discontinue the prednisone. I have scheduled an appointment for blood work to monitor the patient's response to treatment. I will also schedule a follow-up appointment in three months to assess her progress.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nPsoriatic arthritis management.\n\nHISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS\n\nJudy Gomez is a 61-year-old female who presents to the clinic today for ongoing management of psoriatic arthritis.\n\nMs. Gomez is currently taking methotrexate and prednisone 1 mg daily. She believes methotrexate has been relieving her joint pain.\n\nThe patient reports she has been doing well since her last visit. She has been able to decrease her prednisone dose to 1 mg daily; however, she took 2 mg for a couple of days due to increased pain in her bilateral feet.\n\nThe patient states when she received her first COVID-19 vaccine she held her methotrexate and felt \"horrible\" all week until the next Wednesday when she took it. She felt better by the end of the week. She did not hold methotrexate for her second COVID-19 vaccine.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nMusculoskeletal: Full range of motion. Dystrophy of all the nails of the toes.\n\nASSESSMENT\n\n• Psoriatic arthritis.\n• High risk medication use.\n\nPLAN\n\nPsoriatic arthritis.\nStable on methotrexate and prednisone 1 mg daily. The patient will discontinue prednisone and continue methotrexate.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nThe patient will follow up in 3 months.",
